    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-06-23T16:04:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-06-23T16:04:00-05:00" n="11"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d11">
                <head>11. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Algeria</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d11fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 1 ALG–US. Secret. Drafted by
                            <persName corresp="#p_BJJ1">Blake</persName> on June 22; cleared by
                            <persName corresp="#p_THJ1">Tasca</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_HTL2"
                            >Hughes</persName>; and approved and initialed by Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-06-23T17:04:00-04:00">June 23, 1964, 5:04 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2512. For Ambassador. <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 2461.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d11fn2">
                        <ref target="#d10">Document 10</ref>.</note> Aberkane of Algerian Embassy
                    today informed Department <persName corresp="#p_BBA1">Ben Bella</persName> had
                    responded favorably to Secretary’s suggestion re possible desirability quiet and
                    discreet joint inquiry into source allegations <gloss target="#t_CIA1"
                        >CIA</gloss> activities Kabylie.</p>
                <p>Unless you perceive objection, request you contact appropriate level Algerian
                    Government and say <gloss target="#t_DCM1">DCM</gloss> prepared to discuss
                    matter of meeting of representatives suggested during Washington conversation
                        Secretary-<persName corresp="#p_GC1">Guellal</persName>. <gloss
                        target="#t_DCM1">DCM</gloss> should take line (1) US desires any new
                    information Algeria has; (2) repeat in detail previous position; and, (3) unless
                    Algerians indicate they can provide new data, endeavor to close matter by
                    reiterating fact US not supporting opposition to <persName corresp="#p_BBA1">Ben
                        Bella</persName>.<note n="3" xml:id="d11fn3">Telegram 47 to Algiers, July 7,
                        reported that the Department of State informed Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_GC1">Guellal</persName> on July 6 that Norris Haselton had
                        been appointed to meet with a designated Algerian representative in
                        Washington for a joint examination of these allegations. (Department of
                        State, Central Files, <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 9 ALG–US) On July
                        13, Assistant Secretary Williams sent a memorandum to Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName> reporting that <persName
                            corresp="#p_GC1">Guellal</persName> had referred the matter to his
                        government, which had hoped the examination could take place in Algeria.
                        (Ibid.)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD3">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
